I was thinking this would align with how AWSGuard is configured programmatically today:

```json
"config": {
    "all": "mandatory",
    "efs-encrypted": {
        "enforcementLevel": "advisory",
        "kmsKeyId": "the id"
    },
    "ec2-instance-no-public-ip": "advisory"
}
```

Each key would be the policy name and the value is either a string `enforcementLevel` or an object containing the config parameters for the policy (including an optional `enforcementLevel` parameter for specifying that).

I admit that allowing the value to be either a `string` or `object` adds some complexity, but we'll be accepting JSON config from `--policy-pack-config`, and it'd be nice if the structure of that matched the structure used programmatically, since folks will likely be hand-editing the JSON config in the file specified to `--policy-pack-config`, and having the service response match would just keep things simple as we can use the same implementation when parsing the config. (Though, right now in AWSGuard the policy names are [kebab-case](https://wiki.c2.com/?KebabCase), but we programmatically configure them using camelCase).

But if we don't like that, we could force the API response to always use an object for the value, which, for the above example, would look like:

```json
"config": {
    "all": {
        "enforcementLevel": "mandatory"
    },
    "efs-encrypted": {
        "enforcementLevel": "advisory",
        "kmsKeyId": "the id"
    },
    "ec2-instance-no-public-ip": {
        "enforcementLevel": "advisory"
    }
}
```

