> `find` returns the first element satisfying the criteria, `filter` returns all. but yeah, in this context i gues it would do the same thing.

@alexandru-io so why do we execute redundant (& time consuming) calculus instead of preferring this optimization?
As you said in the daily meeting, the overall functionality takes between 2-3 seconds. Every improvements counts, especially if it's not costing too much implementation time.

So instead of adding more parameters here it would be better to do this:
```
    template <
        typename funct,
        typename... Args
        >
    function_evaluation find_min_global (
        thread_pool& tp, 
        funct f,
        const matrix<double,0,1>& bound1,
        const matrix<double,0,1>& bound2,
        const std::vector<bool>& is_integer_variable,
        const std::chrono::nanoseconds max_runtime,
        Args&&... args
    )   
    {   
        return find_min_global(tp, std::move(f), bound1, bound2, is_integer_variable, max_function_calls(), max_runtime, solver_epsilon, std::forward<Args>(args)...);
    } 
```

Then the function that actually implements all this can take these things as parameters and the `stop_condition` can just be a `std::function`.  I would otherwise suggest a universal reference instead of a `std::function` but if someone wants to add more arguments to this function later it will work out better if the type is something more narrow than universal reference.

